description: From Middle English slecken, slekken, from Old Norse slekkja, sløkkva (“to extinguish, quench, slake”), from Proto-Germanic *slakjaną, *slakwijaną (“to slake”), from Proto-Indo-European *(s)lēg- (“weak, faint, limp”). Cognate with Old English sleċċan, slæċċan (“to make slack or slow, delay”).

verbs.description: sleck (third-person singular simple present slecks, present participle slecking, simple past and past participle slecked)

entries.meaning: (dialectal) To slake; allay; cool; quench; extinguish.
(Scotland) To groan when overloaded with food; sigh with repletion.
